104
00:06:02.557 --> 00:06:06.397
So I will explain EMs
because they are useful.

105
00:06:06.397 --> 00:06:10.787
A lot of times we're doing relative sizes.

106
00:06:10.787 --> 00:06:14.958
We want things to be relatively sized
rather than being absolutely sized.

107
00:06:14.958 --> 00:06:17.151
So pixels is an absolute sizing.

108
00:06:17.151 --> 00:06:19.298
It's actually not literally pixels,
just so you know.

109
00:06:19.298 --> 00:06:23.257
But we call them that.

110
00:06:23.257 --> 00:06:27.027
EMs is measured in relation to
what your font choice is, right?

111
00:06:27.027 --> 00:06:33.337
So if I change fonts then I want
the sizing to be relative to the font.

112
00:06:33.337 --> 00:06:37.355
So what it actually does is measure
the width of a lower case m,

113
00:06:37.355 --> 00:06:40.538
something like that,
and that's what m's is.

114
00:06:40.538 --> 00:06:45.973
It's literally EMs long, weird, right?

115
00:06:45.973 --> 00:06:50.517
[LAUGH] But it ends up being really useful
because that means even if you change

116
00:06:50.517 --> 00:06:54.713
fonts, all of your measurement will
change in relation to your font.

117
00:06:56.485 --> 00:07:00.983
&gt;&gt; Brian Holt: It's a little confusing,
but it actually ends up being quite nice.

118
00:07:00.983 --> 00:07:06.374
There's also x ex, and
that's the height of a lower case x.

119
00:07:06.374 --> 00:07:07.223
I never use that one.

120
00:07:07.223 --> 00:07:15.565
[LAUGH] But you can see the CSS tricks
here article to see all the rest of them.

121
00:07:15.565 --> 00:07:20.832
And that's how you write EMs

122
00:07:20.832 --> 00:07:26.767
right there, it's Cool.

